article.description:
The Phoenix Mercury got close the first time. The
second time proved to be the charm and it knocked the Minnesota
Lynx into a more precarious postseason position.
article.headline: DeForge scores 13 of 15 points in 2nd half
article.linkText: Mercury drop Lynx into fourth place out West
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury got close the first time. The second time proved to be the charm and it knocked the Minnesota Lynx into a more precarious postseason position.

Anna DeForge scored 15 points, 13 in the second half, on
Wednesday night to lead Phoenix to a 56-49 victory over Minnesota.

Phoenix (6-20) lost 61-56 at Minnesota on Monday.

"We played them tough at their place and it came down to the
stretch," said DeForge. "It was the same thing tonight. Neither
team shot a very high percentage, but we got to the free throw line
and we took care of the ball better than they did."

Phoenix was 17 of 24 from the foul line to Minnesota's 6 of 9.

Minnesota (15-12) missed its two field-goal attempts and two
free throws after getting within 51-49 with 1:59 remaining.

Coupled with Seattle's 92-56 win over Los Angeles on Wednesday,
the Lynx fell into fourth place in the Western Conference, one game
ahead of Sacramento. The top four teams in each conference make the
WNBA's playoffs. Minnesota travels to Seattle on Friday.

Adrian Williams added 14 points and seven rebounds for Phoenix,
which came in having lost nine of its last 11 games.

"We are looking at this as an opportunity to say, 'Let's start
the season over again," said Williams. "We're a different team
than the one we started the season with."

The Lynx turned the ball over 20 times on Wednesday, allowing
Phoenix to score 21 points off those mistakes.

The second-best shooting team in the league, at 44.9 percent,
was 19-of-53 from the field (36 percent) on Wednesday.

"They play tough defense and make you earn everything," said
Katie Smith.

The Mercury held Smith, the fourth-leading scorer in the WNBA
with a 19.0 average, to 10 points on 4-of-15 shooting. She was just
2-of-9 in the second half. Smith had been held to eight points --
all on free throws -- in the Lynx's win earlier in the week.

Tamika Williams had 12 points and eight rebounds and Janell
Burse added 11 points and nine rebounds for the Lynx, who had won
four of their last five.

"I think they are the only team in the league that plays a
full-court press," said Tamika Williams. "They put a lot of
pressure on you and exert a lot of energy."

Phoenix, which leads the league in steals and had 11 more on
Wednesday, went on a 13-2 run in the second half to take a 49-43
lead with 7:56 left.

Notes: The Mercury played without Kayte Christensen, who was
placed on the injured list with a dislocated left index finger. The
team activated forward Gergana Slavtcheva and center Sonja Mallory
from the injured list. Christensen was averaging 6.6 points and 4.4
rebounds a game before sitting out Monday's game at Minneapolis.
Castro-Marques had scored 4.3 points a game in limited action this
season. Slavtcheva picked up two fouls in two minutes of play on
Wednesday. ... Minnesota is 6-4 since the All-Star break and 1-5 in
its last six games on the road. ... Smith has been the leading
scorer for the Lynx 17 times this season but not in the last four
games. ... The combined 105 points is the fifth lowest in Mercury
franchise history, three of them have been against Minnesota.
